[00:00.20] [The forest.,]
[00:00.40] [A table set out. Enter DUKE SENIOR, AMIENS, and Lords like outlaws]
[00:00.70]DUKE SENIOR I think he be transform'd into a beast;
[00:02.37] For I can no where find him like a man.
[00:04.24]First Lord My lord, he is but even now gone hence:
[00:06.10] Here was he merry, hearing of a song.
[00:07.85]DUKE SENIOR If he, compact of jars, grow musical,
[00:10.02] We shall have shortly discord in the spheres.
[00:12.43] Go, seek him: tell him I would speak with him.
[00:14.48] [Enter JAQUES]
[00:14.80]First Lord He saves my labour by his own approach.
[00:17.09]DUKE SENIOR Why, how now, monsieur! what a life is this,
[00:19.95] That your poor friends must woo your company?
[00:22.63] What, you look merrily!
[00:25.23]JAQUES A fool, a fool! I met a fool i' the forest,
[00:31.13] A motley fool; a miserable world!
[00:33.99] As I do live by food, I met a fool
[00:35.79] Who laid him down and bask'd him in the sun,
[00:37.72] And rail'd on Lady Fortune in good terms,
[00:39.77] In good set terms and yet a motley fool.
[00:43.06] 'Good morrow, fool,' quoth I. 'No, sir,' quoth he,
[00:46.72] 'Call me not fool till heaven hath sent me fortune:'
[00:49.77] And then he drew a dial from his poke,
[00:55.17] And, looking on it with lack-lustre eye,
[00:57.59] Says very wisely, 'It is ten o'clock:
[01:02.99] Thus we may see,' quoth he, 'how the world wags:
[01:06.91] 'Tis but an hour ago since it was nine,
[01:09.46] And after one hour more 'twill be eleven;
[01:13.68] And so, from hour to hour, we ripe and ripe,
[01:16.41] And then, from hour to hour, we rot and rot;
[01:19.64] And thereby hangs a tale.' When I did hear
[01:23.24] The motley fool thus moral on the time,
[01:26.10] My lungs began to crow like chanticleer,
[01:28.71] That fools should be so deep-contemplative,
[01:32.37] And I did laugh sans intermission
[01:36.16] An hour by his dial. O noble fool!
[01:40.07] A worthy fool! Motley's the only wear.
[01:42.62]DUKE SENIOR What fool is this?
[01:44.04]JAQUES O worthy fool! One that hath been a courtier,
[01:46.59] And says, if ladies be but young and fair,
[01:48.71] They have the gift to know it: and in his brain,
[01:51.69] Which is as dry as the remainder biscuit
[01:53.61] After a voyage, he hath strange places cramm'd
[01:56.59] With observation, the which he vents
[01:58.39] In mangled forms. O that I were a fool!
[02:01.75] I am ambitious for a motley coat.
[02:03.86]DUKE SENIOR Thou shalt have one.
[02:04.97]JAQUES It is my only suit;
[02:06.22] Provided that you weed your better judgments
[02:07.95] Of all opinion that grows rank in them
[02:09.76] That I am wise. I must have liberty
[02:12.93] Withal, as large a charter as the wind,
[02:15.29] To blow on whom I please; for so fools have;
[02:18.39] And they that are most galled with my folly,
[02:21.39] They most must laugh. And why, sir, must they so?
[02:25.35] The 'why' is plain as way to parish church:
[02:28.21] He that a fool doth very wisely hit
[02:32.55] Doth very foolishly, although he smart,
[02:35.47] Not to seem senseless of the bob: if not,
[02:38.40] The wise man's folly is anatomized
[02:40.76] Even by the squandering glances of the fool.
[02:43.61] Invest me in my motley; give me leave
[02:47.15] To speak my mind, and I will through and through
[02:49.57] Cleanse the foul body of the infected world,
[02:51.50] If they will patiently receive my medicine.
[02:53.24]DUKE SENIOR Fie on thee! I can tell what thou wouldst do.
[02:56.59]JAQUES What, for a counter, would I do but good?
[02:59.07]DUKE SENIOR Most mischievous foul sin, in chiding sin:
[03:01.87] For thou thyself hast been a libertine,
[03:04.05] As sensual as the brutish sting itself;
[03:06.59] And all the embossed sores and headed evils,
[03:10.26] That thou with licence of free foot hast caught,
[03:12.74] Wouldst thou disgorge into the general world.
[03:15.41]JAQUES Why, who cries out on pride,
[03:17.83] That can therein tax any private party?
[03:20.19] Doth it not flow as hugely as the sea,
[03:23.73] Till that the weary very means do ebb?
[03:26.28] What woman in the city do I name,
[03:29.07] When that I say the city-woman bears
[03:31.50] The cost of princes on unworthy shoulders?
[03:34.47] Who can come in and say that I mean her,
[03:36.77] When such a one as she such is her neighbour?
[03:39.94] Or what is he of basest function
[03:43.23] That says his bravery is not of my cost,
[03:45.97] Thinking that I mean him, but therein suits
[03:48.89] His folly to the mettle of my speech?
[03:51.37] There then; how then? what then? Let me see wherein
[03:54.16] My tongue hath wrong'd him: if it do him right,
[03:56.84] Then he hath wrong'd himself; if he be free,
[03:59.69] Why then my taxing like a wild-goose flies,
