[06:24.46]ORLANDO I thank ye; and be blest for your good comfort!
[06:27.96] [Exit]
[06:28.81]DUKE SENIOR Thou seest we are not all alone unhappy:
[06:32.78] This wide and universal theatre
[06:35.39] Presents more woeful pageants than the scene
[06:37.63] Wherein we play in.
[06:38.99]JAQUES All the world's a stage,
[06:40.37] And all the men and women merely players:
[06:43.40] They have their exits and their entrances;
[06:45.89] And one man in his time plays many parts,
[06:49.68] His acts being seven ages. At first the infant,
[06:53.47] Mewling and puking in the nurse's arms.
[06:56.07] And then the whining school-boy, with his satchel
[06:59.06] And shining morning face, creeping like snail
[07:01.86] Unwillingly to school. And then the lover,
[07:04.77] Sighing like furnace, with a woeful ballad
[07:07.63] Made to his mistress' eyebrow. Then a soldier,
[07:10.98] Full of strange oaths and bearded like the pard,
[07:15.17] Jealous in honour, sudden and quick in quarrel,
[07:17.81] Seeking the bubble reputation
[07:20.19] Even in the cannon's mouth. And then the justice,
[07:24.77] In fair round belly with good capon lined,
[07:28.25] With eyes severe and beard of formal cut,
[07:31.23] Full of wise saws and modern instances;
[07:34.08] And so he plays his part. The sixth age shifts
[07:39.87] Into the lean and slipper'd pantaloon,
[07:41.92] With spectacles on nose and pouch on side,
[07:45.33] His youthful hose, well saved, a world too wide
[07:50.67] For his shrunk shank; and his big manly voice,
[07:54.71] Turning again toward childish treble, pipes
[07:57.76] And whistles in his sound. Last scene of all,
[08:02.66] That ends this strange eventful history,
[08:04.89] Is second childishness and mere oblivion,
[08:06.82] Sans teeth, sans eyes, sans taste, sans everything.
